  <chapter>
  <title>Software for Digital Photo Devices</title>

  <para>
  Unfortunately, many hardware equipment manufacturers refuse to share
  open specifications with potential customers and several millions of
  users who run free operating systems.</para>

  <para>This is a big obstacle to development of free photo
  applications,
  and it blocks free software developers from writing free programs 
  in the future, that supports the same features as the proprietary 
  camera programs for Windows or MacOS that usually are shipped with 
  the camera.   It renders the camera quite useless, if you don't run 
  one of those proprietary operating systems.
  </para>

  <para>Refusing to share free and open camera specifications with
  free software developers is equal to methods Microsoft has said
  (in the <ulink
  url="http://www.opensource.org/halloween/">"Halloween 
  documents"</ulink>) it will use to obstruct free software.</para>

  <para>
  We encourage buyers to boycott the manufacturers with closed-spec
  policies, and companies in the industry to release documentation
  of interfaces between hardware, communications protocols, and new
  file formats to free software developers, who will write drivers.
  </para>

  <para>  
  If your company cannot publish the details, because of some other 
  organization's policy, you should explain briefly why you will 
  continue to market and sell a secret interface, so we can warn 
  other free software users, so they can buy a supported product.
  </para>

  <para>
  That's a fair business policy.
  </para>

